  "response_text": "Recovering from burnout and low energy requires a gentle and gradual approach to diet and exercise. Here's a weekly routine that can help:\n\n**Important:** Before starting any new diet or exercise routine, consult with your doctor or a healthcare professional, especially if you have any underlying medical conditions.\n\n**Diet:**\n\n1. **Hydration:** Drink at least 8-10 glasses of water per day.\n2. **Balanced meals:** Focus on whole, unprocessed foods like:\n\t* Leafy greens (spinach, kale, collard greens)\n\t* Fresh fruits (berries, citrus fruits, apples)\n\t* Nuts and seeds (almonds, walnuts, chia seeds)\n\t* Whole grains (brown rice, quinoa, whole wheat bread)\n\t* Lean proteins (chicken, fish, tofu)\n\t* Healthy fats (avocado, olive oil, coconut oil)\n3. **Meal frequency:** Eat 3 main meals and 2-3 snacks per day to maintain stable energy levels.\n4. **Avoid:** Sugary drinks, caffeine, and processed foods that can exacerbate burnout and low energy.\n\n**Sample Meal Plan:**\n\nMonday:\n\n* Breakfast: Oatmeal with banana, almond butter, and honey\n* Lunch: Grilled chicken breast with quinoa, roasted vegetables, and avocado\n* Snack: Apple slices with peanut butter\n* Dinner: Baked salmon with sweet potato, green beans, and brown rice\n\nTuesday:\n\n* Breakfast: Scrambled eggs with whole wheat toast and mixed berries\n* Lunch: Lentil soup with whole grain bread and a side salad\n* Snack: Greek yogurt with honey and walnuts\n* Dinner: Grilled turkey breast with roasted vegetables and quinoa\n\nWednesday:\n\n* Breakfast: Smoothie bowl with spinach, banana, almond milk, and almond butter topping\n* Lunch: Grilled chicken breast with mixed greens, whole wheat wrap, and avocado\n* Snack: Carrot sticks with hummus\n* Dinner: Baked chicken thighs with roasted broccoli, brown rice, and olive oil\n\nThursday:\n\n* Breakfast: Avocado toast with scrambled eggs and cherry tomatoes\n* Lunch: Quinoa salad with grilled chicken, mixed vegetables, and a citrus vinaigrette dressing\n* Snack: Cottage cheese with cucumber slices\n* Dinner: Grilled shrimp with roasted asparagus, quinoa, and olive oil\n\nFriday:\n\n* Breakfast: Whole grain waffles with mixed berries, yogurt, and granola\n* Lunch: Chicken Caesar salad with whole wheat croutons\n* Snack: Hard-boiled egg with cherry tomatoes\n* Dinner: Baked chicken breast with roasted Brussels sprouts, sweet potato, and brown rice\n\n**Workout Routine:**\n\n1. **Start slow:** Begin with 10-15 minute workouts, 2-3 times a week, and gradually increase duration and frequency.\n2. **Gentle exercises:** Focus on low-impact activities that promote relaxation and energy:\n\t* Yoga (Hatha, Yin, or Restorative)\n\t* Walking\n\t* Swimming\n\t* Cycling (stationary or outdoor)\n\t* Stretching\n3. **Listen to your body:** Rest and recover when needed. If you experience fatigue, dizziness, or pain, stop and consult with your doctor or healthcare professional.\n\n**Sample Workout Plan:**\n\nMonday (15 minutes):\n\n* 5-minute warm-up (light stretching or walking)\n* 5-minute yoga (focus on breathing and gentle stretches)\n* 5-minute cool-down (stretching and relaxation)\n\nWednesday (20 minutes):\n\n* 5-minute warm-up (light cardio or walking)\n* 10-minute swimming or cycling (low-intensity)\n* 5-minute cool-down (stretching and relaxation)\n\nFriday (20 minutes):\n\n* 5-minute warm-up (light stretching or walking)\n* 10-minute yoga (focus on balance and strength)\n* 5-minute cool-down (stretching and relaxation)\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n1. **Get enough sleep:** Aim for 7-9 hours of sleep per night to help your body recover.\n2. **Practice stress-reducing techniques:** Try meditation, deep breathing, or progressive muscle relaxation to manage stress and anxiety.\n3. **Connect with nature:** Spend time outdoors, whether it's walking, hiking, or simply sitting in a park or garden.\n4. **Seek social support:** Reach out to friends, family, or a therapist for emotional support and connection.\n\nRemember, recovering from burnout and low energy takes time, patience, and self-care. Be gentle with yourself, and don't hesitate to seek professional help if you need additional guidance or support.",
